   <h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><i>Index of Economic Freedom</i></h1> 
   <div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content"> 
    <div id="siteSub" class="noprint">
     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
    </div> 
    <div id="contentSub"></div> 
    <div id="contentSub2"></div> 
    <div id="jump-to-nav"></div> <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">Jump to navigation</a> <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">Jump to search</a> 
    <div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr">
     <div class="mw-parser-output">
      <div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">
       Annual index and ranking created in 1995 by The Heritage Foundation and The Wall Street Journal to measure the degree of economic freedom in the world's nations
      </div> 
      <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">
       This article is about the index published by the Wall Street Journal and the Heritage Foundation. For other indices, see <a href="/wiki/Indices_of_economic_freedom" title="Indices of economic freedom">Indices of economic freedom</a>.
      </div> 
      <p class="mw-empty-elt"> </p> 
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:402px;">
        <a href="/wiki/File:Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png/400px-Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png" decoding="async" width="400" height="205" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png/600px-Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png/800px-Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png 2x" data-file-width="5393" data-file-height="2766"></a> 
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a href="/wiki/File:Index_of_Economic_Freedom_2018.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a>
         </div>The 2018 Heritage Foundation Index of Economic Freedom overall heatmap
        </div>
       </div>
      </div> 
      <p>The <i><b>Index of Economic Freedom</b></i> is an annual index and ranking created in 1995 by <a href="/wiki/The_Heritage_Foundation" title="The Heritage Foundation">The Heritage Foundation</a> and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Wall_Street_Journal" title="The Wall Street Journal">The Wall Street Journal</a></i> to measure the degree of <a href="/wiki/Economic_freedom" title="Economic freedom">economic freedom</a> in the world's nations. The creators of the index took an approach similar to <a href="/wiki/Adam_Smith" title="Adam Smith">Adam Smith's</a> in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Wealth_of_Nations" title="The Wealth of Nations">The Wealth of Nations</a></i>, that "basic institutions that protect the liberty of individuals to pursue their own economic interests result in greater prosperity for the larger society".<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-freedom_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-freedom-2">[2]</a></sup> </p> 
      <div id="toc" class="toc" role="navigation" aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading">
       <input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none">
       <div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr">

      </div> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Purpose">Purpose</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Purpose">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>The Heritage Foundation website states that "Economic freedom is the fundamental right of every human to control his or her own labor and property. In an economically free society, individuals are free to work, produce, consume, and invest in any way they please. In economically free societies, governments allow labor, capital, and goods to move freely, and refrain from coercion or constraint of liberty beyond the extent necessary to protect and maintain liberty itself."<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup> By publishing yearly reports the foundation attempts to highlight where such freedoms do and don't exist. </p>
      <p>The Heritage Foundation reports that the top 20% on the index have twice the per capita income of those in the second quintile, and five times that of the bottom 20%.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Carl_Schramm" title="Carl Schramm">Carl Schramm</a>, who wrote the first chapter of the 2008 Index, states that cities of Medieval Italy and mid-19th century Midwestern American cities all flourished to the degree they possessed economic fluidity and institutional adaptiveness created by economic freedom.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>According to <a href="/wiki/Will_Wilkinson" title="Will Wilkinson">Will Wilkinson</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Libertarianism" title="Libertarianism">libertarian</a> <a href="/wiki/Think_tank" title="Think tank">think tank</a> <a href="/wiki/Cato_Institute" title="Cato Institute">Cato Institute</a>, studies show that higher economic freedom correlates strongly with higher self-reported happiness.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> According to economists Tomi Ovaska and Ryo Takashima, economic freedom research suggests "that people unmistakably care about the degree to which the society where they live provides them opportunities and the freedom to undertake new projects, strongly with and make choices based on one's personal preferences."<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>According to the Cato Institute, higher economic freedom promotes participation and collaboration.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup> Also claimed is that higher economic freedom is extremely significant in preventing wars; according to their calculations, freedom is around 54 times more effective than democracy (as measured by <i>Democracy Score</i>) in diminishing violent conflict.<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Ratings">Ratings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Ratings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>Since the index was created in 1995, the score for world economic freedom has increased, rising 2.6 points up to 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup> In 2011 the score had decreased from the 2008 score of 60.2 to 59.7, which represents an increase of 2.2 points since 1995. The Economic Freedom score improved for 117 countries, the majority of countries included in the index, which were mainly <a href="/wiki/Developing_country" title="Developing country">developing</a> and <a href="/wiki/Emerging_markets" class="mw-redirect" title="Emerging markets">emerging market</a> economies. With the exception of <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and <a href="/wiki/North_America" title="North America">North America</a>, there were increased levels of freedom recorded in all regions, with the greatest improvement shown in <a href="/wiki/Sub-Saharan_Africa" title="Sub-Saharan Africa">Sub-Saharan Africa</a>. The top five "free" economies identified by the 2011 index were <a href="/wiki/Hong_Kong" title="Hong Kong">Hong Kong</a>, <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">Singapore</a>, <a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">New Zealand</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a>, each scoring over 80 on the economic freedom grading scale.<sup id="cite_ref-Exec11_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Exec11-11">[11]</a></sup> Since the Index was created in 1995, Hong Kong has been the top performing economy.<sup id="cite_ref-Exec11_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Exec11-11">[11]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>In 2011, the United States dropped to 9th place behind such countries as Denmark, Canada, and first-place Hong Kong.<sup id="cite_ref-Exec11_11-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Exec11-11">[11]</a></sup> The Heritage Foundation has pointed to increases in government spending as the reason for the United States' decline, and according to data from the 2011 index, the growth rates of countries with the highest levels of government spending were 4.5 points lower, on average, than countries where government spending was under control.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup> In their "Executive Highlights" of index results, the Heritage Foundation stated that "high levels of government spending in response to the global economic turmoil have not resulted in higher economic growth".<sup id="cite_ref-Exec11_11-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Exec11-11">[11]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The results from the 2012 index showed an overall decline in global economic freedom; according to The Heritage Foundation, the average score in its ranking was the second lowest of the last ten years.<sup id="cite_ref-APJan12_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-APJan12-14">[14]</a></sup> In particular, the U.S. dropped to 10th place in the ranking, and has now fallen three places since 2008, when it was 7th.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> A report issued by the Foundation stated that government spending was the cause of the decline, and had "not only failed to arrest the economic crisis, but also - in many countries - seems to be prolonging it".<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup> According to the report, activity in the private sector is threatened by the greater government spending, which has increased public debt and led to more bureaucracy.<sup id="cite_ref-APJan12_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-APJan12-14">[14]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Countries that shared the same rank received a tie score. </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Reception">Reception</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Reception">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>According to the <a href="/wiki/Freedom_House" title="Freedom House">Freedom House</a>, "there is a high and statistically significant correlation between the level of political freedom as measured by Freedom House and economic freedom as measured by the Wall Street Journal/Heritage Foundation survey."<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Millennium_Challenge_Account" class="mw-redirect" title="Millennium Challenge Account">Millennium Challenge Account</a>, a U.S. government foreign aid program, has used the Trade freedom indicator in determining which countries will receive their performance-based compacts.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Critics such as <a href="/wiki/Jeffrey_Sachs" title="Jeffrey Sachs">Jeffrey Sachs</a> have contested the Index's assumption that economic openness necessarily leads to better growth. In his book <i><a href="/wiki/The_End_of_Poverty" title="The End of Poverty">The End of Poverty</a></i>, Sachs graphed countries' ratings on the index against GDP per capita growth between 1995 and 2003, claiming to demonstrate no correlation between a country's rating and its rate of economic growth. Sachs pointed out, as examples, that countries with good ratings such as Switzerland and Uruguay had sluggish economic performances, others, like China, with poorer rating had very strong economic growth.<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The <a href="/wiki/UAE" class="mw-redirect" title="UAE">UAE</a> questioned the rating of their country's economic freedom in 2008, comparing its middling rating with the high rating they had received from other indicators such as <a href="/wiki/Transparency_International" title="Transparency International">Transparency International</a> and <a href="/wiki/Moody%27s" class="mw-redirect" title="Moody's">Moody's</a>. They also argued that the report is "unreliable", because its methodology had changed twice in the last two years.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>Stefan Karlsson of the <a href="/wiki/Ludwig_von_Mises_Institute" class="mw-redirect" title="Ludwig von Mises Institute">Ludwig von Mises Institute</a> challenged the usefulness of the index due to the fuzziness of many of the categories used to determine freedom.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup> John Miller roundly criticizes the "Index", writing in <i><a href="/wiki/Dollars_%26_Sense" title="Dollars &amp; Sense">Dollars &amp; Sense</a></i>, "In the hands of the Wall Street Journal and the Heritage Foundation, Washington's foremost right-wing think tank, however, an economic freedom index merely measures corporate and entrepreneurial freedom from accountability. Upon examination, the index turns out to be a poor barometer of either freedom more broadly construed or of prosperity."<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup> According to Left Business Observer, growth in Index accounts for 10% of the variation in the growth of GDP.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Methodology">Methodology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Methodology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <p>The ranking scores aspects of economic freedom between 0 and 100, with 0 meaning "no economic freedom" and 100 meaning "total economic freedom". There are twelve aspects divided into four categories.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup> </p> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rule_of_law">Rule of law</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Rule of law">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Property_rights">Property rights</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Property rights">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Degree of a country's legal protection of private property rights and degree of enforcement of those laws. It is divided into the following sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>physical property rights</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Intellectual_property" title="Intellectual property">intellectual property</a> rights</li> 
       <li>strength of investor protection</li> 
       <li>risk of <a href="/wiki/Expropriation" class="mw-redirect" title="Expropriation">expropriation</a></li> 
       <li>quality of land administration</li>
      </ol> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Judicial_effectiveness">Judicial effectiveness</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Judicial effectiveness">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Degree of the <a href="/wiki/Judiciary" title="Judiciary">judiciary</a>'s efficiency and fairness, especially dealing with property laws. It is divided into the following sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>judicial independence</li> 
       <li>quality of the <a href="/wiki/Judicial_process" class="mw-redirect" title="Judicial process">judicial process</a></li> 
       <li>likelihood of obtaining favorable judicial decisions</li>
      </ol> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Government_integrity">Government integrity</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Government integrity">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Analyzes how prevalent are forms of <a href="/wiki/Political_corruption" title="Political corruption">political corruption</a> and practices such as <a href="/wiki/Bribery" title="Bribery">bribery</a>, <a href="/wiki/Extortion" title="Extortion">extortion</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nepotism" title="Nepotism">nepotism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cronyism" title="Cronyism">cronyism</a>, <a href="/wiki/Patronage" title="Patronage">patronage</a>, <a href="/wiki/Embezzlement" title="Embezzlement">embezzlement</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Graft_(politics)" title="Graft (politics)">graft</a>. It is divided into the following sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li><a href="/wiki/Public_trust" title="Public trust">public trust</a> in politicians</li> 
       <li>irregular payments and bribes</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Open_government" title="Open government">transparency</a> of government <a href="/wiki/Policymaking" class="mw-redirect" title="Policymaking">policymaking</a></li> 
       <li>absence of corruption</li> 
       <li><a href="/wiki/Corruption_Perceptions_Index" title="Corruption Perceptions Index">perceptions of corruption</a></li> 
       <li>governmental and civil service transparency</li>
      </ol> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Government_size">Government size</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Government size">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Tax_burden">Tax burden</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Tax burden">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Analyzes <a href="/wiki/Marginal_tax" class="mw-redirect" title="Marginal tax">marginal tax</a> rates on personal and corporate income and the overall taxation level (including direct and indirect taxes imposed by all levels of government) as a percentage of the <a href="/wiki/GDP" class="mw-redirect" title="GDP">GDP</a>. Its sub-factors are: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>top marginal tax rate on individual income</li> 
       <li>top marginal tax rate on corporate income</li> 
       <li>total tax burden as a percentage of GDP</li>
      </ol> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Government_spending">Government spending</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Government spending">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Quantifies the burden of <a href="/wiki/Government_expenditure" class="mw-redirect" title="Government expenditure">government expenditures</a>, including consumption by the state and all transfer payments related to various <a href="/wiki/Entitlement_program" class="mw-redirect" title="Entitlement program">entitlement programs</a>. The ideal level varies from country to country, but zero expenditure is used as a benchmark. </p> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Fiscal_health">Fiscal health</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Fiscal health">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Analyzes how well a country manages its budget by quantifying the growing <a href="/wiki/Debt" title="Debt">debt</a> and <a href="/wiki/Government_budget_deficit" class="mw-redirect" title="Government budget deficit">deficit</a>. It is divided into the following sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>average deficits as a percentage of GDP for the most recent three years (80 percent of score)</li> 
       <li>debt as a percentage of GDP (20 percent of score)</li>
      </ol> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Regulatory_efficiency">Regulatory efficiency</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Regulatory efficiency">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Business_freedom">Business freedom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Business freedom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Analyses the cost, time and freedom to open, operate and close a business, taking into consideration factors like electricity. It is divided into thirteen sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>starting a business - procedures (number);</li> 
       <li>starting a business - time (days);</li> 
       <li>starting a business - cost (% of income per capita);</li> 
       <li>starting a business - minimum capital (% of income per capita);</li> 
       <li>obtaining a license - procedures (number);</li> 
       <li>obtaining a license - time (days);</li> 
       <li>obtaining a license - cost (% of income per capita);</li> 
       <li>closing a business - time (years);</li> 
       <li>closing a business - cost (% of estate);</li> 
       <li>closing a business - recovery rate (cents on the dollar);</li> 
       <li>getting electricity - procedures (number);</li> 
       <li>getting electricity - time (days); and</li> 
       <li>getting electricity - cost (% of income per capita).</li>
      </ol> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Labor_freedom">Labor freedom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Labor freedom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Quantifies the intrusiveness of <a href="/wiki/Labor_rights" title="Labor rights">labor rights</a> such as <a href="/wiki/Minimum_wage" title="Minimum wage">minimum wage</a>, laws inhibiting layoffs, severance requirements, and measurable regulatory restraints on hiring and hours worked, plus the labor force participation rate as an indicative measure of employment opportunities in the labor market. It is divided into the following sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>ratio of minimum wage to the average value added per worker</li> 
       <li>hindrance to hiring additional workers</li> 
       <li>rigidity of hours</li> 
       <li>difficulty of firing redundant employees</li> 
       <li>legally mandated notice period</li> 
       <li>mandatory severance pay</li> 
       <li>labor force participation rate</li>
      </ol> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Monetary_freedom">Monetary freedom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Monetary freedom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Analyses how stable are prices and how much <a href="/wiki/Microeconomy" class="mw-redirect" title="Microeconomy">microeconomy</a> intervenes. It is divided into the following sub-factors: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>weighted average <a href="/wiki/Inflation_rate" class="mw-redirect" title="Inflation rate">inflation rate</a> for the most recent three years</li> 
       <li>price controls</li>
      </ol> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Market_openness">Market openness</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Market openness">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Trade_freedom">Trade freedom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Trade freedom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Quantifies the extent to which <a href="/wiki/Tariff" title="Tariff">tariff</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nontariff_barriers" class="mw-redirect" title="Nontariff barriers">nontariff barriers</a> affect <a href="/wiki/Imports" class="mw-redirect" title="Imports">imports</a> and <a href="/wiki/Exports" class="mw-redirect" title="Exports">exports</a> of goods and services into and out of the country. Its sub-factors are: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>trade-weighted average tariff rate</li> 
       <li>nontariff barriers (NTBs)</li>
      </ol> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Investment_freedom">Investment freedom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Investment freedom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Analyses how free or constrained is the flow of <a href="/wiki/Investment_capital" class="mw-redirect" title="Investment capital">investment capital</a> of individuals and firms. </p> 
      <h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Financial_freedom">Financial freedom</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Financial freedom">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4> 
      <p>Indicates <a href="/wiki/Bank" title="Bank">banking</a> efficiency as well as how independent the government is from the financial sector. This aspect looks at five broad areas: </p> 
      <ol>
       <li>extent of government regulation of financial services</li> 
       <li>degree of state intervention in banks and other financial firms through direct and indirect ownership</li> 
       <li>government influence on the allocation of credit</li> 
       <li>extent of financial and capital market development</li> 
       <li>openness to foreign competition</li>
      </ol> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Previous_Methodology">Previous Methodology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Previous Methodology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>The Index's 2008 definition of economic freedom is "the highest form of economic freedom provides an absolute right of property ownership, fully realized freedoms of movement for labor, capital, and goods, and an absolute absence of coercion or constraint of economic liberty beyond the extent necessary for citizens to protect and maintain liberty itself."<sup id="cite_ref-index_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-index-25">[25]</a></sup> </p>
      <p>The index scores nations on ten factors of economic freedom, separated into four categories, using statistics from organizations like the <a href="/wiki/World_Bank" title="World Bank">World Bank</a>, the <a href="/wiki/International_Monetary_Fund" title="International Monetary Fund">International Monetary Fund</a>, <a href="/wiki/Economist_Intelligence_Unit" title="Economist Intelligence Unit">Economist Intelligence Unit</a> and <a href="/wiki/Transparency_International" title="Transparency International">Transparency International</a>. In each factor, countries are scored 0 to 100, with 0 being the least free and 100 the most free. A score of 100 signifies an economic environment or set of policies that is most conducive to economic freedom.<sup id="cite_ref-index_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-index-25">[25]</a></sup> The methodology has shifted and changed as new data and measurements have become available, especially in the area of Labor Freedom, which was given its own indicator spot in 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-freedom_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-freedom-2">[2]</a></sup> The following list explains what each factor currently assesses and groups them according to their respective category: </p> 
      <dl>
       <dt>
        Rule of Law
       </dt>
      </dl> 
      <ul>
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/property-rights">Property Rights</a></b>: Degree of a country's legal protection of private property rights, degree of enforcement of those laws, independence of and corruption within the <a href="/wiki/Judiciary" title="Judiciary">judiciary</a>, and likelihood of <a href="/wiki/Expropriation" class="mw-redirect" title="Expropriation">expropriation</a>.</li> 
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/freedom-from-corruption">Freedom from Corruption</a></b>: The non-prevalence of <a href="/wiki/Political_corruption" title="Political corruption">political corruption</a> within a country, according to the <a href="/wiki/Corruption_Perceptions_Index" title="Corruption Perceptions Index">Corruption Perceptions Index</a>.</li>
      </ul> 
      <dl>
       <dt>
        Limited Government
       </dt>
      </dl> 
      <ul>
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/fiscal-freedom">Fiscal Freedom</a></b>: How free is a country from tax burden. It comprises three quantitative measures: top marginal tax rate of both individual (1) and corporate (2) income, and total tax burden as a percentage of GDP (3).</li> 
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/government-spending">Government Size/Spending</a></b>: Governments' expenditures as a percentage of GDP, including consumption and transfers. The higher the percentual spending, the lower the score.</li>
      </ul> 
      <dl>
       <dt>
        Regulatory Efficiency
       </dt>
      </dl> 
      <ul>
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/business-freedom">Business Freedom</a></b>: A country's freedom from the burden of regulations on starting, operating, and closing business, given factors such as time, cost and number of procedures, as well as the efficiency of government in the regulatory process.</li> 
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/labor-freedom">Labor Freedom</a></b>: How free is a country from legal regulation on the labor market, including those relating to minimum wages, hiring and firing, hours of work and severance requirements.</li> 
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/monetary-freedom">Monetary Freedom</a></b>: How free from microeconomic intervention and price instability is a country, basing on an equation considering the weighted average inflation rate in the last three years and price controls.</li>
      </ul> 
      <dl>
       <dt>
        Open Markets
       </dt>
      </dl> 
      <ul>
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/trade-freedom">Trade Freedom</a></b>: Freedom from sizeable numbers and burdens of <a href="/wiki/Tariff" title="Tariff">tariffs</a> and <a href="/wiki/Non-tariff_barriers_to_trade" title="Non-tariff barriers to trade">non-tariff barriers</a> to imports and exports of a country.</li> 
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/investment-freedom">Investment Freedom</a></b>: Freedom from restrictions on the movement and use of investment capital, regardless of activity, within and across the country's borders.</li> 
       <li><b><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.heritage.org/index/financial-freedom">Financial Freedom</a></b>: A country's independence from government control and interference in the financial sector, including banks. It considers government ownership of financial firms, extent of financial and capital market development, government influence on the allocation of credit and openness to foreign competition.</li>
      </ul> 
      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Rankings">Rankings</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Rankings">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> 
      <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2020_Index">2020 Index</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: 2020 Index">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3> 
      <p>As of 2020, <a href="/wiki/Singapore" title="Singapore">Singapore</a>’s economic freedom score is 89.4, making it the world’s freest economy in the 2020 Index. Singapore is ranked 1st among 42 countries in the <a href="/wiki/Asia-Pacific" title="Asia-Pacific">Asia-Pacific</a> region, and its overall score is well above the regional and world averages. </p>
      <p><i>Key: <span style="color:#2b6b2e;">██</span> Free (80–100)</i> <i><span style="color:#43a847;">██</span>&nbsp;Mostly&nbsp;Free&nbsp;(70–79.9)</i> <i><span style="color:#dcaa41;">██</span>&nbsp;Moderately&nbsp;Free&nbsp;(65–69.9)</i> <i><span style="color:#c68c32;">██</span>&nbsp;Moderately&nbsp;Unfree&nbsp;(60–64.9)</i> <i><span style="color:#c84e19;">██</span>&nbsp;Mostly&nbsp;Unfree&nbsp;(55–59.9)</i> <i><span style="color:#b8220e;">██</span>&nbsp;Mostly&nbsp;Unfree&nbsp;(50–54.9)</i> <i><span style="color:#f51405;">██</span>&nbsp;Repressed&nbsp;(0–49.9)</i> </p>

         <th>Change </th>
        </tr>

        <tr> 
         <td style="text-align:left;"><span class="flagicon"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Flag_of_New_Zealand.svg/23px-Flag_of_New_Zealand.svg.png" decoding="async" width="23" height="12" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Flag_of_New_Zealand.svg/35px-Flag_of_New_Zealand.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Flag_of_New_Zealand.svg/46px-Flag_of_New_Zealand.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="600">&nbsp;</span><a href="/wiki/New_Zealand" title="New Zealand">New Zealand</a> </td>

        </tr> 
        <tr> 
         <td style="text-align:left;"><span class="flagicon"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg/23px-Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg.png" decoding="async" width="23" height="12" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg/35px-Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/88/Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg/46px-Flag_of_Australia_%28converted%29.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1280" data-file-height="640">&nbsp;</span><a href="/wiki/Australia" title="Australia">Australia</a> </td>

      <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="2020_Index_in_full">2020 Index in full</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Index_of_Economic_Freedom&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: 2020 Index in full">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
